## Why This Is Asked
This question tests practical knowledge of end-to-end streaming ingestion on GCP with privacy and governance considerations. It evaluates the candidate's ability to apply core GCP primitives—including Pub/Sub, Dataflow, BigQuery, and Data Catalog—while addressing real-world concerns like multi-tenancy, data quality, and operational resilience.

## Key Concepts
- **Streaming Ingestion**: Pub/Sub for real-time event capture, Dataflow for scalable processing
- **Per-Tenant Isolation**: Shared raw table architecture with Authorized Views for secure multi-tenancy
- **Data Governance**: Data Catalog for schema registry and lineage tracking
- **Data Quality**: Schema enforcement, null validation, and statistical anomaly detection
- **Operational Concerns**: Late-arrival handling, rollback procedures, and schema evolution

## Code Example
```javascript
// Skeleton DoFn to compute 3-sigma anomalies
class AnomalyDetectionDoFn extends DoFn {
  processElement(element) {
    const mean = this.meanField; // Pre-computed per tenant
    const stdDev = this.stdDevField;
    const threshold = 3 * stdDev;
    const value = element.numericField;
    const isAnomaly = Math.abs(value - mean) > threshold;
    // Output with anomaly flag
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would the design scale to hundreds of tenants while preserving isolation?
- What are the cost implications of the dead-letter queue approach for schema drift?
- How would you monitor data quality metrics in production?

## Why This Is Asked
